is evil plan that he had devised against the Jews should return on his own head, and that he and his sons should be hanged on the gallows.</span><span class=\"v17_9_26\"><sup id=\"Esth.9.26\" class=\"v17_9_26\">26</sup>Therefore they called these days Purim, after the term Pur. Therefore, because of all that was written in this letter, and of what they had faced in this matter, and of what had happened to them, </span><span class=\"v17_9_27\"><sup id=\"Esth.9.27\" class=\"v17_9_27\">27</sup>the Jews firmly obligated themselves and their offspring and all who joined them, that without fail they would keep these two days according to what was written and at the time appointed every year, </span><span class=\"v17_9_28\"><sup id=\"Esth.9.28\" class=\"v17_9_28\">28</sup>that these days should be remembered and kept throughout every generation, in every clan, province, and city, and that these days of Purim should never fall into disuse among the Jews, nor should the commemoration of these days cease among their descendants.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p\"><span class=\"v17_9_29\"><sup id=\"Esth.9.29\" class=\"v17_9_29\">29</sup>Then Queen Esther, the daughter of Abihail, and Mordecai the Jew gave full written authority, confirming this second letter about Purim. </span><span class=\"v17_9_30\"><sup id=\"Esth.9.30\" class=\"v17_9_30\">30</sup>Letters were sent to all the Jews, to the 127 provinces of the kingdom of Ahasuerus, in words of peace and truth, </span><span class=\"v17_9_31\"><sup id=\"Esth.9.31\" class=\"v17_9_31\">31</sup>that these days of Purim should be observed at their appointed seasons, as Mordecai the Jew and Queen Esther obligated them, and as they had obligated themselves and their offspring, with regard to their fasts and their lamenting. </span><span class=\"v17_9_32\"><sup id=\"Esth.9.32\" class=\"v17_9_32\">32</sup>The command of Queen Esther confirmed these practices of Purim, and it was recorded in writing.</span></p>\n</div>\n", 
